results.notes:
Collected. Odor weak/indistinct. No apparent staining/bruising.
Some clustered with some in the cluster a maintaining or developing significant dark brownish-red wash on stipe, primarily in the middle and/or upper portions. The stipes are rather long and quite firm. The base is white and swollen (amount varies- some subtle, a few rather obvious), but bulbs never with a prominent distinct rim. The interior of the base/bulb is a light brown, very much like pale wood at a hardware store. The rest of the context pale creamy to light brown, but is more yellow-shaded.
On the caps, note the mahogany to dark reddish color toward the margins. The rest of the cap is a very muted hodgepodge of other colors, but generally palest as a light brown toward the center or where the fruitbody had been covered with much dirt (this is fairly visible in photos). Cap surface smooth and dry upon collection, apparently had been viscid before, but I doubt were ever too slimy. Some caps got a little darker after collecting (maybe sun exposure?), but this definitely isn’t one of the “blackening” cort species.
The gills begin a dull yellowish color (visible in the photos, always similar to those shown) before eventually browning out in the color of the spore print.
Under deciduous oaks. A madrone, tanoak and mixed-conifer forest is within sight of the location, but these very likely are oak-associated.
KOH negative on all parts, except slightly yellowish perhaps on cap exterior.
